SIMPLE: doctrinal
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: doctrinal
<hw>doc"tri*nal</hw> <pr>(d⟦ocr⟧k"tr⟦icr⟧*n⟦ait⟧l)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<ety>[LL. <ets>doctrinalis</ets>, fr. L. <ets>doctrina</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>doctrinal</ets>. See <er>Doctrine</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Pertaining to, or containing, doctrine or something taught and to
be believed; <as>as, a <ex>doctrinal</ex> observation</as>.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Doctrinal</xex> clauses.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Macaulay.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Pertaining to, or having to do with,
teaching.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The word of God serveth no otherwise than in the nature of a
<qex>doctrinal</qex> instrument.</q> <rj><qau> Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Doctrinal</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Doctrinal
<hw>Doc"tri*nal</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A matter of doctrine; also, a
system of doctrines.</def> <rj><au>T. Goodwin. Sir T.
Elyot.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Doctrinally</ent>⟦br⟧
